@NODE Introduction "Raindir Guide 1.1 Copyright ® 1994 Kimmo Pekkola"

1. Introduction

	This is my first released utility(?) for Amiga (though I havent't made
    anything for any other computer either). Since now I've made couple of Demos
    and intros by the name Rainman of DiskNet. I've made also small tools which
    were never released (they're for my personal use only).

	But why new dir? What's wrong with the old one? Well, nothing really,
    Its output is just so booooring! I've been using the MasterDir v2.0 by
    Corsair of Dragons since it produces a bit nicer (colorful) output, but
    as it is a quite old prod (and bugged) I decided to make my own and better.


    NOTE: It is not allowed to give this production for free (unless you have a
	  really good reason to do so). You must take a decent amount of money
	  to cover up all your expencises (the more the better :). Everyone who
	  disobeys the rule WILL be prosecuted (and found guilty). 
@ENDNODE

@NODE Usage "Raindir Guide 1.1 Copyright ® 1994 Kimmo Pekkola"

2. Using Raindir

	The reason why I am using Raindir and not any other dir (No, I don't
    use c-shell or similar either) is because I like to show off My WB. I have 
    64 color WB with 64 color bg-pictures (mostly Hajimes) and MagicWB of
    course. And everything looks extrimely cool (and colorful).

	There is nothing wrong with the other Directory commands. It's just
    that they look so plain. One color output is hardly what I want to see
    on my WB. I know that more colors means less speed, but I think you can
    cope with that, after all if you compare the speed of 64 color WB to any
    other Graphical Operating System (e.g. Windows) it is UltraFast.

	The output is designed to use MagicWB colors so it may look a bit
    strange if you don't have 'em.

        Please note that I don't take any responsibility if your HD might crash
    while using this production nor do I take responsibility for any other kind
    of data loss or physical / mental damage to you or your computer.  

@ENDNODE

@NODE F&F "Raindir Guide 1.1 Copyright ® 1994 Kimmo Pekkola"

3. Features 

    Raindir has couple of nice features which are compiled below:

     À It was coded in 100% Assembler (which means that it may have some
       unexpected bugs in it)

     À It generates its output to fit in your window (wider the window more
       columns you get)

     À Detects different fontsizes

     À Centers the path-name and puts it in a gadget like 3D-box (Though
       nothing happens if you push it :)

     À Displays useful info about the dir and the disk

     À From version 1.1 Raindir uses ReadArgs(). Arguments currently known are:

	@{fg shine}COMMENT@{fg text}		Prints out comments (window sensitive)

	@{fg shine}DEFAULT@{fg text}		Uses defauls values (width=80 height=infinite)

	@{fg shine}FLAGS@{fg text}		Prints flags and dates (window sensitive)

	@{fg shine}HORIZONTAL@{fg text}	Sorts horizontally (check the difference)

	@{fg shine}LENGHT@{fg text}		If you like to use different lenght in columns 
			(@{fg shine}LENGHT 20@{fg text} will produce four 20 chars wide columns
			on default window)

	@{fg shine}COLUMNS@{fg text}		If you want to use different number of columns in your
			output (@{fg shine}COLUMNS 1@{fg text} will produce only one column). You
			can combine @{fg shine}LENGHT@{fg text} and @{fg shine}COLUMNS@{fg text} to generate almost any
			kind of output. 

	@{fg shine}PAUSE@{fg text}		Pause after one page is printed

	@{fg shine}SINCE@{fg text}		Print only files which are newer than given date
			(@{fg shine}SINCE@{fg text} today will show files that have been made today)

     À Possibly lots of nice little things which I am not gonna tell you
       here (Find out something yourself! It shouldn't be too complicated) 


 WARNING: I am not sure if I consider the following a feature, but I might
	  as well inform you of it: Sometimes Raindir goes wacko and randomly
	  destroys parts of your disks (harddisks included) completely...



	  ... Nah! No it doesen't. I'm only kidding!



	  ... Or am I?
@ENDNODE

